WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:18.040
There is a bsthemepreview function that, like, given that you don't already have a Shiny

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:26.320
application that you want to preview a theme for, you can give bsthemepreview, like, if

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:33.599
I had this, if I already had in mind, like, a theme that I wanted to use and didn't want

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:43.060
to do the work of actually, like, programming a Shiny app example, I can just save this

00:00:43.060 --> 00:01:01.060
theme here and use this bs, bstheme, preview, give it a theme. And it will apply that theme

00:01:01.060 --> 00:01:09.019
to this demo, like, Shiny demo app that kind of tries its best to stuff all of, like, the

00:01:09.019 --> 00:01:16.900
core Shiny UI stuff that we support into this example app. So, you can see, like, how

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:22.779
those styles would end up affecting, like, slider input and selectize input and date

00:01:22.779 --> 00:01:33.019
input, as well as things like, you know, verbatim text output and, like, all of the sort of

00:01:33.019 --> 00:01:42.900
Shiny widgets that you may or may not be already used to. And then it also, at the

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:53.180
same time, overlays this interactive widget that I can drag around and use to make tweaks

00:01:53.180 --> 00:02:03.139
to the actual theme settings. So, I can change from, like, a something closer to a black

00:02:03.139 --> 00:02:11.539
to something closer to, like, an ice blue theme. So, it's got the two main background

00:02:11.539 --> 00:02:21.100
and foreground colors. It's also got the ability to use a boot swatch theme, if you want to.

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:27.779
Just be aware, like, if you use a boot swatch theme, don't expect, like, the custom theming

00:02:27.779 --> 00:02:35.619
options to always work super great with it. So, just want to set expectations there that,

00:02:35.619 --> 00:02:41.300
like, just because of the way that boot swatch is currently set up, they haven't, like, implemented

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:49.139
those themes well enough in mind to, like, allow you to tweak them in ways that work

00:02:49.179 --> 00:02:58.139
as well as just using the default bootstrap theme. So, just be aware of that. So, you can

00:02:58.139 --> 00:03:03.660
change the main, like, background foreground, as well as, you know, I could have a different

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:12.860
primary color here. That will change, like, tab set panel, things like check boxes and radio

00:03:12.860 --> 00:03:21.820
buttons, slider inputs. Also, you know, we try our best to kind of use those, like, main

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:28.940
semantics of bootstrap and propagate them throughout all of the widgets that we provide in Shiny.

00:03:31.979 --> 00:03:39.580
So, yeah, the main, like, color and boot swatch settings, as well as fonts. And again,

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:49.020
this has integration with Google Fonts, where I could choose any Sans Serif font that I wanted.

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:57.899
Let's choose something like, I'm not sure how to pronounce this one, but I do like it, Montserrat.

00:04:00.220 --> 00:04:02.699
So, I could change from Pront to Montserrat.

00:04:03.660 --> 00:04:09.179
Oh, and actually, that might be a bug, that it seems to have gone back to my original theme

00:04:09.179 --> 00:04:17.500
settings. But now, you can see, like, at the top here and on the tab set panels, it's kind of

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:25.739
slightly different looking font here. It also has thematic enabled, so that we can look at how

00:04:25.739 --> 00:04:33.500
the theme would actually be propagated to our plots defaults settings, as well. So, I could,

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:40.459
again, change to, like, a blue color here, and that will just automatically kind of propagate

00:04:40.459 --> 00:04:49.660
to the R plot. Same thing with, like, DT tables. DT also has some nice integration with BS Lib,

00:04:50.059 --> 00:04:59.660
where it derives its sort of accent colors and main colors and fonts, as well. All those styles

00:04:59.660 --> 00:05:08.940
from the BS Lib theme. And then, you know, these are just some other things that we provide in

00:05:08.940 --> 00:05:17.660
Shiny UI, like modals and progress bars, notifications. And then, like, the difference

00:05:17.739 --> 00:05:21.739
between, you know, how the heading fonts would look versus code and base font.

00:05:24.059 --> 00:05:30.299
And then, some other kind of more low-level options for more advanced theming. So,

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:41.179
if you can see my R console here, various output that has been essentially echoed as I've made

00:05:41.179 --> 00:05:48.540
changes to the theming application. And it should do a good job of keeping track of just the

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:56.540
changes that you've made interactively. So, like, this captures the fact that I've changed to a,

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:01.339
you know, more of a blue background and foreground color, as well as the Montserrat

00:06:01.899 --> 00:06:12.540
font setting. And it's not quite smart enough to know, like, that it should actually integrate

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:18.940
this stuff with the input theme that you've given it. So, you will have to essentially, like, copy

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:27.500
this code here. And it does make the assumption that your theme is named theme. But thankfully,

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:34.299
I've actually used the name theme. So, I can just say BS theme update this theme with these new

00:06:34.299 --> 00:06:42.299
settings. And now, you know, if I feed this in to input, again, on the BS theme preview,

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:50.140
it will use the Montserrat settings. The BS theme preview is really nice if you're, like,

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:56.619
again, you don't already have a Shiny app that you're using and you want to, like, get a feel for

00:06:58.380 --> 00:07:03.820
what colors and fonts you might want to use in your future Shiny app. But if you already have

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:11.500
an existing Shiny app, you can leverage that same interactive theming widget. So, if I already have

00:07:12.059 --> 00:07:12.299
this

00:07:16.059 --> 00:07:23.019
nav bar page here, I can first let me actually

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:30.779
do more of a traditional looking setup. And here's the server function

00:07:31.339 --> 00:07:37.500
which has the input and output arguments as well as session.

00:07:39.980 --> 00:07:49.500
And then BS lib has a function called BS themer that you can call inside of your

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:55.339
server function. And then it will overlay

00:07:59.339 --> 00:08:04.059
that same interactive themer on this particular Shiny app.

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:10.779
So, now I could go in and do the same thing to my basic nav bar page.

00:08:11.019 --> 00:08:16.859
And still get the same experience of, like, the code being output to replicate the changes.

00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:23.579
And you don't necessarily, like, you just need to call this once. You don't need to worry about,

00:08:23.579 --> 00:08:26.940
like, calling this in a reactive context or anything like that.

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:30.779
Like, if you want to do this, just go to the top of your server function

00:08:31.899 --> 00:08:36.780
and call this function once. And then it will just

00:08:36.859 --> 00:08:43.739
overlay that. And you can also collapse it if you don't actually really want to use it.

00:08:45.419 --> 00:08:49.820
And you want to, like, do some other stuff with your Shiny app, you can collapse it and kind of

00:08:49.820 --> 00:08:55.020
get it out of your way if you don't want it anymore. And, yeah, not only can you do this

00:08:55.020 --> 00:09:01.179
with Shiny, but you can also do this with your R Markdown documents. But there is it's a little

00:09:02.059 --> 00:09:08.539
bit more tricky to figure out how to do that. In the sense that it requires two different things.

00:09:09.419 --> 00:09:18.619
It requires you to add a runtime Shiny to your R Markdown document. Because, really,

00:09:19.419 --> 00:09:25.820
we can't get the full features of this interactive theming widget working without

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:32.539
a Shiny runtime. And then, as well, sort of, like, in your setup chunk,

00:09:35.340 --> 00:09:42.380
you want to call this BSThemer. Sort of like how you call the BSThemer in the server function.

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:51.020
You want to do the same thing in code that's going to run in a server context.

00:09:51.659 --> 00:09:59.020
In code that's going to run in a server context. Which I can't remember if that's

00:10:01.179 --> 00:10:05.340
well, actually, that did looks like that worked. So, we got this original

00:10:06.539 --> 00:10:11.739
example that we were working from. And now this interactive themer. So, if I wanted to,

00:10:11.739 --> 00:10:17.020
like, have a look at one of these prepackaged themes, say, Minty.

00:10:21.099 --> 00:10:25.020
I can see how that will look on my R Markdown document.

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:36.539
Unfortunately, thematic won't work if you're statically rendering these plots. So, it doesn't

00:10:36.539 --> 00:10:42.219
know that, like, by default, it won't know to, like, rerender itself when your theme has changed.

00:10:43.099 --> 00:10:51.900
But you can make that work, as well, if you, instead, dynamically render this through a

00:10:51.900 --> 00:10:59.580
render plot. Which now we can do, because we have the runtime Shiny, like, we can render

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:09.500
have the ability to render our plots dynamically. So, if I let's just make sure this works by

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:19.739
stopping and running again. All right. So, it's recognized the default theme.

00:11:19.739 --> 00:11:31.179
But now if I change to Minty, it will know to rerender itself with those new CSS settings,

00:11:31.179 --> 00:11:36.700
essentially.

